Certainly! Here's a **complete, working stack implementation in Rust**.
This implementation uses a `Vec<T>` internally and exposes typical stack operations: `push`, `pop`, `peek`, `is_empty`, and `len`.

```rust
// Stack implementation in Rust
pub struct Stack<T> {
    items: Vec<T>,
}

impl<T> Stack<T> {
    /// Creates a new empty stack
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Stack { items: Vec::new() }
    }

    /// Pushes an item onto the stack
    pub fn push(&mut self, item: T) {
        self.items.push(item);
    }

    /// Pops the top item off the stack, or None if empty
    pub fn pop(&mut self) -> Option<T> {
        self.items.pop()
    }

    /// Returns a reference to the top item, or None if empty
    pub fn peek(&self) -> Option<&T> {
        self.items.last()
    }

    /// Returns the number of items in the stack
    pub fn len(&self) -> usize {
        self.items.len()
    }

    /// Returns true if the stack is empty
    pub fn is_empty(&self) -> bool {
        self.items.is_empty()
    }
}

// Example usage
fn main() {
    let mut stack = Stack::new();

    stack.push(10);
    stack.push(20);
    stack.push(30);

    println!("Stack length: {}", stack.len());
    println!("Top item: {:?}", stack.peek());

    while !stack.is_empty() {
        println!("Popped: {:?}", stack.pop());
    }
}
```

**How it works:**

- `Stack<T>` is generic, works with any type.
- Uses a `Vec<T>` internally for storage.
- `push`, `pop`, and `peek` operate as you'd expect for a stack (LIFO).
- `len` and `is_empty` provide info about the stack status.
- The example usage shows pushing, peeking, popping, and printing values.

