Here’s a **complete, working B-tree implementation in Rust** with insertion and search. This is a basic implementation for educational purposes, supporting integer keys and values. For brevity, this code does **not** include deletion or balancing complexities beyond standard B-tree insertion. The B-tree order (`T`) (minimum degree) is customizable.

```rust
use std::cmp::Ordering;

const T: usize = 2; // Minimum degree (B-Tree order): Each node can have 2..=2*T children

#[derive(Debug)]
struct BTreeNode {
    keys: Vec<i32>,
    values: Vec<i32>,
    children: Vec<Box<BTreeNode>>,
    leaf: bool,
}

impl BTreeNode {
    fn new(leaf: bool) -> Self {
        BTreeNode {
            keys: Vec::new(),
            values: Vec::new(),
            children: Vec::new(),
            leaf,
        }
    }

    fn search(&self, key: i32) -> Option<i32> {
        let mut i = 0;
        while i < self.keys.len() && key > self.keys[i] {
            i += 1;
        }
        if i < self.keys.len() && self.keys[i] == key {
            return Some(self.values[i]);
        }
        if self.leaf {
            None
        } else {
            self.children[i].search(key)
        }
    }

    // Insert a new key and value into the subtree rooted at this node.
    // Assumes this node is not full when called (keys.len() < 2*T - 1)
    fn insert_non_full(&mut self, key: i32, value: i32) {
        let mut i = self.keys.len();
        if self.leaf {
            // Insert in sorted order
            while i > 0 && key < self.keys[i - 1] {
                i -= 1;
            }
            self.keys.insert(i, key);
            self.values.insert(i, value);
        } else {
            while i > 0 && key < self.keys[i - 1] {
                i -= 1;
            }
            // If the child is full, split it
            if self.children[i].keys.len() == 2 * T - 1 {
                self.split_child(i);
                if key > self.keys[i] {
                    i += 1;
                }
            }
            self.children[i].insert_non_full(key, value);
        }
    }

    // Split child at children[i] into two nodes and move middle key up
    fn split_child(&mut self, i: usize) {
        let y = &mut self.children[i];
        let mut z = Box::new(BTreeNode::new(y.leaf));

        // z gets T-1 keys from y
        z.keys = y.keys.split_off(T);
        let middle_key = y.keys.pop().unwrap();
        z.values = y.values.split_off(T);
        let middle_value = y.values.pop().unwrap();

        if !y.leaf {
            z.children = y.children.split_off(T);
        }

        self.keys.insert(i, middle_key);
        self.values.insert(i, middle_value);
        self.children.insert(i + 1, z);
    }
}

#[derive(Debug)]
pub struct BTree {
    root: Option<Box<BTreeNode>>,
}

impl BTree {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        BTree { root: None }
    }

    pub fn search(&self, key: i32) -> Option<i32> {
        match &self.root {
            Some(root) => root.search(key),
            None => None,
        }
    }

    pub fn insert(&mut self, key: i32, value: i32) {
        if let Some(root) = &mut self.root {
            if root.keys.len() == 2 * T - 1 {
                // Root is full, split it
                let mut new_root = Box::new(BTreeNode::new(false));
                new_root.children.push(root.take());
                new_root.split_child(0);
                self.root = Some(new_root);
            }
            self.root.as_mut().unwrap().insert_non_full(key, value);
        } else {
            let mut root = Box::new(BTreeNode::new(true));
            root.keys.push(key);
            root.values.push(value);
            self.root = Some(root);
        }
    }
}

// Helper for moving Box around during split
trait Take {
    fn take(&mut self) -> Box<BTreeNode>;
}
impl Take for Box<BTreeNode> {
    fn take(&mut self) -> Box<BTreeNode> {
        // Replaces this box with an empty leaf node
        std::mem::replace(self, Box::new(BTreeNode::new(true)))
    }
}

// ------------------- Test code ---------------------
fn main() {
    let mut bt = BTree::new();
    let keys = [10, 20, 5, 6, 12, 30, 7, 17];

    for &k in &keys {
        bt.insert(k, k * 100);
    }

    for &k in &keys {
        println!(
            "Search {}: {:?}",
            k,
            bt.search(k)
        );
    }

    // Should print None for missing keys
    println!("Search 99: {:?}", bt.search(99));

    // Print the tree structure for debugging
    println!("{:#?}", bt);
}
```

### Explanation

- **T** is the minimum degree of the B-tree, i.e., minimum number of children for internal nodes. You can change this as needed.
- `BTreeNode` stores keys, values, and child nodes.
- `insert` splits full nodes as necessary and inserts keys and values.
- `search` finds a key linearly in a node and recursively searches children.
- `main` tests the insertion and search features.

---

**Note:**  
This code is for learning; it does not implement deletion, nor generic types, and the search is linear per node. For practical applications, use Rust's [`BTreeMap`](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/collections/struct.BTreeMap.html).  
