- Previous versions (`t0`) remain unchanged after insert.

**References**

- Balancing pattern is from Chris Okasaki's functional red-black trees ([See paper](https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~rwh/courses/afp/lectures/afp-trees.pdf)).
- Uses `Rc` for sharing.

**Note:** This code supports **insert** and **lookup**. Deletion is more complex and not included here, but can be added similarly. This is a strong, functional foundation for persistent search trees in Rust.

**Implementing a Tri-color Garbage Collector in Rust**

Below is a minimal **tri-color mark-and-sweep garbage collector** in Rust. This example is **educational**, not production-ready! We’ll handle:

- Mark (tri-color: White=Unreachable, Gray=Reachable-unscanned, Black=Reachable-scanned)
- Sweep (collect white objects)
- Manual root registration (no language integration)
- Objects have references to other objects via `Gc` pointers

### `GcColor` and Object

```rust
// The color states
#[derive(Copy, Clone, PartialEq, Debug)]
enum GcColor {
    White,
    Gray,
    Black,
}

// The managed object type
struct GcObject {
    color: GcColor,
    // For demo, each object holds references to other objects
    children: Vec<Gc<GcObject>>,
    value: String, // some payload
}
```

### Gc: Managed Pointer

We use `Rc<RefCell<GcObject>>` for safe pointer, mutability across GC.

```rust
use std::rc::Rc;
use std::cell::RefCell;

// Our "Gc" pointer: just a wrapper
#[derive(Clone)]
struct Gc<T>(Rc<RefCell<T>>);

impl<T> Gc<T> {
    fn new(value: T) -> Gc<T> {
        Gc(Rc::new(RefCell::new(value)))
    }
    fn borrow(&self) -> std::cell::Ref<T> { self.0.borrow() }
    fn borrow_mut(&self) -> std::cell::RefMut<T> { self.0.borrow_mut() }
}
```

### The GC Heap

```rust
struct Heap {
    objects: Vec<Gc<GcObject>>,
    roots: Vec<Gc<GcObject>>,
}
```

### Mark (tri-color)

```rust
impl Heap {
    fn mark(&mut self) {
        // Set all objects to White
        for obj in &self.objects {
            obj.borrow_mut().color = GcColor::White;
        }
        // All roots to Gray
        for root in &self.roots {
            root.borrow_mut().color = GcColor::Gray;
        }
        // Process gray objects
        let mut gray_stack: Vec<Gc<GcObject>> = self.roots.clone();
        while let Some(obj) = gray_stack.pop() {
            let mut obj_ref = obj.borrow_mut();
            // For each child: if white, mark gray and push to stack
            for child in obj_ref.children.iter() {
                let mut child_ref = child.borrow_mut();
                if child_ref.color == GcColor::White {
                    child_ref.color = GcColor::Gray;
                    gray_stack.push(child.clone());
                }
            }
            obj_ref.color = GcColor::Black;
        }
    }
```

### Sweep

```rust
    fn sweep(&mut self) {
        // Remove any object that remains white
        self.objects.retain(|obj| obj.borrow().color != GcColor::White);
    }
```

### Allocation

```rust
    fn alloc(&mut self, value: String) -> Gc<GcObject> {
        let obj = Gc::new(GcObject {
            color: GcColor::White,
            children: vec![],
            value,
        });
        self.objects.push(obj.clone());
        obj
    }

    fn add_root(&mut self, obj: &Gc<GcObject>) {
        self.roots.push(obj.clone());
    }

    fn remove_root(&mut self, obj: &Gc<GcObject>) {
        self.roots.retain(|root| !Rc::ptr_eq(&root.0, &obj.0));
    }
}
```

### Full Demo, Including `main`

```rust
use std::rc::Rc;
use std::cell::RefCell;

// The color states
#[derive(Copy, Clone, PartialEq, Debug)]
enum GcColor {
    White,
    Gray,
    Black,
}

struct GcObject {
    color: GcColor,
    children: Vec<Gc<GcObject>>,
    value: String,
}

#[derive(Clone)]
struct Gc<T>(Rc<RefCell<T>>);

impl<T> Gc<T> {
    fn new(value: T) -> Gc<T> {
        Gc(Rc::new(RefCell::new(value)))
    }
    fn borrow(&self) -> std::cell::Ref<T> { self.0.borrow() }
    fn borrow_mut(&self) -> std::cell::RefMut<T> { self.0.borrow_mut() }
}

struct Heap {
    objects: Vec<Gc<GcObject>>,
    roots: Vec<Gc<GcObject>>,
}

impl Heap {
    fn new() -> Self {
        Heap { objects: vec![], roots: vec![] }
    }

    fn alloc(&mut self, value: String) -> Gc<GcObject> {
        let obj = Gc::new(GcObject {
            color: GcColor::White,
            children: vec![],
            value,
        });
        self.objects.push(obj.clone());
        obj
    }

    fn add_root(&mut self, obj: &Gc<GcObject>) {
        self.roots.push(obj.clone());
    }
    fn remove_root(&mut self, obj: &Gc<GcObject>) {
        self.roots.retain(|root| !Rc::ptr_eq(&root.0, &obj.0));
    }

    fn mark(&mut self) {
        // Set all objects to White
        for obj in &self.objects {
            obj.borrow_mut().color = GcColor::White;
        }
        // All roots to Gray
        for root in &self.roots {
            root.borrow_mut().color = GcColor::Gray;
        }
        // Process gray objects
        let mut gray_stack: Vec<Gc<GcObject>> = self.roots.clone();
        while let Some(obj) = gray_stack.pop() {
            let mut obj_ref = obj.borrow_mut();
            // For each child: if white, mark gray and push to stack
            for child in obj_ref.children.iter() {
                let mut child_ref = child.borrow_mut();
                if child_ref.color == GcColor::White {
                    child_ref.color = GcColor::Gray;
                    gray_stack.push(child.clone());
                }
            }
            obj_ref.color = GcColor::Black;
        }
    }

    fn sweep(&mut self) {
        let before = self.objects.len();
        self.objects.retain(|obj| obj.borrow().color != GcColor::White);
        let after = self.objects.len();
        println!("Swept: {} unreachable objects", before - after);
    }

    fn collect(&mut self) {
        self.mark();
        self.sweep();
    }

    fn dump(&self) {
        println!("Heap dump:");
        for obj in &self.objects {
            let o = obj.borrow();
            println!("  '{}', color={:?}, children={}", o.value, o.color, o.children.len());
        }
    }
}

fn main() {
    let mut heap = Heap::new();

    // Allocate and link objects
    let a = heap.alloc("A".to_string());
    let b = heap.alloc("B".to_string());
    let c = heap.alloc("C".to_string());
    let d = heap.alloc("D".to_string());

    // Setup graph: A->B, B->C, C->A (cycle), D alone
    a.borrow_mut().children.push(b.clone());
    b.borrow_mut().children.push(c.clone());
    c.borrow_mut().children.push(a.clone());

    // Register roots
    heap.add_root(&a);

    println!("Before GC:");
    heap.dump();

    heap.collect();

    println!("After GC:");
    heap.dump();

    // Now remove root, leaving nothing reachable
    heap.remove_root(&a);
    heap.collect();

    println!("After removing root:");
    heap.dump();
}
```

---

**How this works:**

- **Heap** stores all objects, and manual roots.
- **Mark** colors reachable objects (via root and child pointers) black.
- **Sweep** deletes white objects.
- Cycles are collected if unreachable from roots.

---

**Usage:**
- Save to `main.rs`, `cargo run` -- should show unreachable objects getting swept.
- To extend: manage roots naturally, handle more types, thread safety, integration with interpreter, etc.

---

**Reference**: Tri-color GC is classic; this Rust code models the standard algorithm. For more advanced GC, see crates like [`gc`](https://github.com/Manishearth/rust-gc) for production-quality solutions!

Sure! Below is a **complete Rust implementation** of a basic SQL `SELECT` parser. This parser supports queries like:

```sql
SELECT col1, col2 FROM table WHERE col1 = 'value'
```

It parses:

- The columns,
- The table name,
- The (very basic) WHERE clause (column, operator, and value).

Of course, this is a simple parser and **not fully SQL-compliant**—but it's good for learning and small use-cases!

---

## Complete Rust Implementation

You need the [`regex`](https://docs.rs/regex/) crate for parsing.

**Cargo.toml**:
```toml
[package]
name = "sql_select_parser"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
regex = "1"
```

**src/main.rs**:
```rust
use regex::Regex;

#[derive(Debug)]
struct SelectStatement {
    columns: Vec<String>,
    table: String,
    where_clause: Option<WhereClause>,
}

#[derive(Debug)]
struct WhereClause {
    column: String,
    operator: String,
    value: String,
}

fn parse_select(sql: &str) -> Result<SelectStatement, String> {
    // Remove leading/trailing whitespace and semicolon
    let sql = sql.trim().trim_end_matches(';').to_string();

    // Regex for SELECT statement
    // Captures: columns (1), table (2), where clause (3, optional)
    let re = Regex::new(
        r"(?si)^SELECT\s+(?P<columns>.+?)\s+FROM\s+(?P<table>\w+)(?:\s+WHERE\s+(?P<where>.+))?$"
    ).unwrap();

    let caps = re.captures(&sql).ok_or("Invalid SELECT syntax")?;

    // Parse columns
    let columns_str = caps.name("columns").unwrap().as_str();
    let columns: Vec<String> = columns_str
        .split(',')
        .map(|s| s.trim().to_string())
        .collect();

    // Parse table
    let table = caps.name("table").unwrap().as_str().to_string();

    // Parse where clause (simple col op value)
    let where_clause = if let Some(where_str) = caps.name("where") {
        let where_src = where_str.as_str();

        // Simple operator parsing: =, <>, >, <, >=, <=
        let where_re = Regex::new(
            r"(?i)^(?P<column>\w+)\s*(?P<op>=|<>|>=|<=|>|<)\s*('?.+?'?|[^\s]+)$"
        ).unwrap();
        let wcaps = where_re.captures(where_src)
            .ok_or("Invalid WHERE clause syntax")?;

        let column = wcaps.name("column").unwrap().as_str().to_string();
        let operator = wcaps.name("op").unwrap().as_str().to_string();
        let value = wcaps.get(3).unwrap().as_str().trim().trim_matches('\'').to_string();

        Some(WhereClause { column, operator, value })
    } else {
        None
    };

    Ok(SelectStatement {
        columns,
        table,
        where_clause,
    })
}

fn main() {
    let queries = vec![
        "SELECT col1, col2 FROM table",
        "SELECT col1 FROM users WHERE name = 'Alice'",
        "SELECT id,name FROM persons WHERE age > 30;",
        "SELECT   col1,col2,col3   FROM    my_table   WHERE  status = 'active'"
    ];

    for sql in queries {
        println!("Parsing: {}", sql);
        match parse_select(sql) {
            Ok(stmt) => println!("Parsed: {:#?}\n", stmt),
            Err(e) => println!("Error: {}\n", e),
        }
    }
}
```

---

