Here's a fully working implementation of an **LRU (Least Recently Used) Cache** in Rust.

This uses the standard library only, so it's easy to use in any Rust project. It provides `get`, `put`, and `len` methods. Note the use of `std::collections::HashMap` for fast key lookup, and a `VecDeque` (from `std::collections`) for tracking usage order, though for better performance a linked list can be used. For simplicity and clarity, this implementation is easy to read and understand.

## Complete Rust Implementation

```rust
use std::collections::{HashMap, VecDeque};
use std::hash::Hash;

/// An LRU Cache
pub struct LruCache<K, V> {
    map: HashMap<K, V>,
    order: VecDeque<K>,
    capacity: usize,
}

impl<K, V> LruCache<K, V>
where
    K: Clone + Eq + Hash,
{
    /// Create a new LRU cache with specified capacity.
    pub fn new(capacity: usize) -> Self {
        Self {
            map: HashMap::with_capacity(capacity),
            order: VecDeque::with_capacity(capacity),
            capacity,
        }
    }

    /// Get a value by key. Updates usage order.
    pub fn get(&mut self, key: &K) -> Option<&V> {
        if self.map.contains_key(key) {
            // Move key to the front.
            self.promote(key);
            self.map.get(key)
        } else {
            None
        }
    }

    /// Put a key-value pair into the cache.
    pub fn put(&mut self, key: K, value: V) {
        if self.map.contains_key(&key) {
            // Update value and usage order.
            self.promote(&key);
            self.map.insert(key.clone(), value);
        } else {
            // If full, remove least used.
            if self.map.len() == self.capacity {
                if let Some(lru) = self.order.pop_back() {
                    self.map.remove(&lru);
                }
            }
            self.order.push_front(key.clone());
            self.map.insert(key, value);
        }
    }

    /// Remove a key from usage order and reinsert at front (most used).
    fn promote(&mut self, key: &K) {
        if let Some(pos) = self.order.iter().position(|k| k == key) {
            self.order.remove(pos);
            self.order.push_front(key.clone());
        }
    }

    /// Returns current number of elements.
    pub fn len(&self) -> usize {
        self.map.len()
    }

    /// Is the cache empty?
    pub fn is_empty(&self) -> bool {
        self.map.is_empty()
    }
}

// Simple test
#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn basic_lru() {
        let mut cache = LruCache::new(2);
        cache.put(1, "one");
        cache.put(2, "two");
        assert_eq!(cache.get(&1), Some(&"one")); // Access key 1
        cache.put(3, "three"); // Should evict key 2
        assert_eq!(cache.get(&2), None);
        assert_eq!(cache.get(&1), Some(&"one"));
        assert_eq!(cache.get(&3), Some(&"three"));
        cache.put(4, "four"); // Evicts key 1
        assert_eq!(cache.get(&1), None);
        assert_eq!(cache.get(&3), Some(&"three"));
        assert_eq!(cache.get(&4), Some(&"four"));
    }
}
```

---

## Usage Example

```rust
fn main() {
    let mut cache = LruCache::new(3);
    cache.put("apple", 10);
    cache.put("banana", 20);
    cache.put("cherry", 30);

    println!("{:?}", cache.get(&"apple")); // Some(10)

    cache.put("durian", 40); // Evicts banana

    println!("{:?}", cache.get(&"banana")); // None
    println!("{:?}", cache.get(&"cherry")); // Some(30)
}
```

---

## Notes

- This implementation is generic over key (`K`) and value (`V`), requires `K: Clone + Eq + Hash`.
- For maximal performance, a more complex (but faster) double-linked-list structure could be used (see [linked-hash-map crate](https://docs.rs/linked-hash-map)), but this is simple, safe, and correct.
- The `order` vector holds keys from most recent (front) to least recent (back).

