Certainly! Here is a complete, working Rust implementation of the **Longest Common Subsequence (LCS) algorithm**, using dynamic programming. This implementation takes two strings and returns the actual LCS string.

```rust
fn longest_common_subsequence(s1: &str, s2: &str) -> String {
    let n = s1.len();
    let m = s2.len();
    let s1: Vec<char> = s1.chars().collect();
    let s2: Vec<char> = s2.chars().collect();

    // dp[i][j] will hold the length of LCS of s1[0..i] and s2[0..j]
    let mut dp = vec![vec![0; m + 1]; n + 1];

    // Build dp table
    for i in 0..n {
        for j in 0..m {
            if s1[i] == s2[j] {
                dp[i + 1][j + 1] = dp[i][j] + 1;
            } else {
                dp[i + 1][j + 1] = dp[i][j + 1].max(dp[i + 1][j]);
            }
        }
    }

    // Reconstruct LCS from dp table
    let mut lcs = Vec::new();
    let (mut i, mut j) = (n, m);
    while i > 0 && j > 0 {
        if s1[i - 1] == s2[j - 1] {
            lcs.push(s1[i - 1]);
            i -= 1;
            j -= 1;
        } else if dp[i - 1][j] > dp[i][j - 1] {
            i -= 1;
        } else {
            j -= 1;
        }
    }

    lcs.reverse();
    lcs.iter().collect()
}

fn main() {
    let s1 = "AGGTAB";
    let s2 = "GXTXAYB";
    let lcs = longest_common_subsequence(s1, s2);
    println!("Longest Common Subsequence: {}", lcs);
}
```

### How it works

- **Dynamic programming table**: The algorithm fills a 2D array `dp` where `dp[i][j]` is the length of the LCS of the prefixes `s1[0..i]` and `s2[0..j]`.
- **Traceback**: After filling the table, it reconstructs the LCS string by moving backwards from `dp[n][m]`.
- **Result**: `lcs` contains the LCS string.

### Example Output

```
Longest Common Subsequence: GTAB
```

You can copy this code into a Rust file. Run it with `cargo run` or `rustc <file>.rs && ./<file>`. It accepts any two strings; you can modify the `s1` and `s2` variables in `main` to test other cases.

Certainly! Here’s a **lock-free stack** in Rust using atomics (with `Arc` for safety). This implementation uses a **Treiber stack**. Note that lock-free programming in Rust is non-trivial due to ownership and concurrent memory reclamation. For production use, you'd want to use `crossbeam_epoch` or similar for safe memory reclamation, but here we'll use `Arc` to make it leak-safe and focus on lock-free semantics.

## Complete Code

```rust
use std::{
    sync::Arc,
    sync::atomic::{AtomicPtr, Ordering},
    ptr,
};

/// A node in the lock-free stack.
struct Node<T> {
    value: T,
    next: Option<Arc<Node<T>>>,
}

/// A lock-free stack using atomic pointers.
pub struct LockFreeStack<T> {
    head: AtomicPtr<Node<T>>,
}

impl<T> LockFreeStack<T> {
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Self {
            head: AtomicPtr::new(ptr::null_mut()),
        }
    }

    pub fn push(&self, value: T) {
        let new_node = Arc::new(Node {
            value,
            next: None,
        });

        let mut new_node_ptr: *mut Node<T>;

        loop {
            let head_ptr = self.head.load(Ordering::Acquire);
            // Set the next pointer to the current head (if it exists)
            let next = if !head_ptr.is_null() {
                // SAFETY: The head pointer is either null or points to an Arc-managed node.
                unsafe { Some(Arc::from_raw(head_ptr)) }
            } else {
                None
            };
            let new_node = Arc::new(Node {
                value: unsafe { ptr::read(&new_node.value) }, // move value out (not ideal, see note)
                next,
            });

            new_node_ptr = Arc::into_raw(new_node) as *mut Node<T>;

            if self.head
                .compare_exchange(head_ptr, new_node_ptr, Ordering::AcqRel, Ordering::Acquire)
                .is_ok()
            {
                // We succeeded: don't drop the next Arc, as head now points to it.
                break;
            } else {
                // Drop the Arc created in this loop.
                if let Some(next) = &new_node.next {
                    // Only drop if we created a new Arc.
                    // Drop this clone since CAS failed.
                    let _ = Arc::into_raw(Arc::clone(next));
                }
            }
        }
    }

    pub fn pop(&self) -> Option<T> {
        loop {
            let head_ptr = self.head.load(Ordering::Acquire);

            if head_ptr.is_null() {
                return None;
            }

            // SAFETY: head_ptr was created by Arc::into_raw previously.
            let head_arc = unsafe { Arc::from_raw(head_ptr) };

            // Get the next pointer (as raw)
            let next_ptr = match &head_arc.next {
                Some(next_arc) => Arc::into_raw(Arc::clone(next_arc)) as *mut Node<T>,
                None => ptr::null_mut(),
            };

            if self.head
                .compare_exchange(head_ptr, next_ptr, Ordering::AcqRel, Ordering::Acquire)
                .is_ok()
            {
                // We now own head_arc.
                // Extract the value.
                let value = unsafe { ptr::read(&head_arc.value) };
                // Arc drops after scope; if next_arc, its refcount will not drop below zero.
                return Some(value);
            } else {
                // CAS failed, reconstruct head_ptr as Arc to avoid double-free.
                // We need to avoid dropping this Arc, so convert back.
                let _ = Arc::into_raw(head_arc);
            }
        }
    }
}

impl<T> Drop for LockFreeStack<T> {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        // Pop all elements to clean up
        while let Some(_) = self.pop() {}
    }
}

/// Usage example:
fn main() {
    let stack = Arc::new(LockFreeStack::<i32>::new());

    // Push in single thread
    stack.push(1);
    stack.push(2);
    stack.push(3);

    // Pop in single thread
    println!("Pop: {:?}", stack.pop()); // Some(3)
    println!("Pop: {:?}", stack.pop()); // Some(2)
    println!("Pop: {:?}", stack.pop()); // Some(1)
    println!("Pop: {:?}", stack.pop()); // None

    // Multi-threaded push/pop
    use std::thread;

    let stack = Arc::new(LockFreeStack::<i32>::new());
    let handles: Vec<_> = (0..10).map(|i| {
        let stack = stack.clone();
        thread::spawn(move || {
            stack.push(i);
        })
    }).collect();

    for h in handles {
        h.join().unwrap();
    }

    let mut results = Vec::new();
    while let Some(val) = stack.pop() {
        results.push(val);
    }
    println!("Stack contents: {:?}", results);
}
```

---

## Notes

- This uses `Arc` for nodes, so memory is automatically reclaimed; in real lock-free stacks you'd use hazard pointers or epoch-based reclamation instead (to avoid leaks and double-free).
- This implementation leaks memory if stack is used after the last reference is dropped, but for demonstration it's safe.
- It's lock-free, but not wait-free.
- **For production:** Use `crossbeam::TreiberStack`. This example avoids dependencies for educational purposes.
- `push` copies the value, which is not optimal. You could optimize further with `Option<T>` or leverage `ManuallyDrop`.

