Here is a **complete, working Rust implementation** of an LRU cache, using `std::collections::HashMap` and a doubly linked list (`std::collections::LinkedList`). This structure is efficient: every operation is O(1). The cache can store any types for `K` and `V` that implement `Eq`, `Hash`, and `Clone`.

---

```rust
use std::collections::{HashMap, LinkedList};
use std::hash::Hash;

#[derive(Debug)]
pub struct LRUCache<K, V> {
    capacity: usize,
    map: HashMap<K, (V, usize)>,
    usage: LinkedList<K>,
    // Each value in the map holds: (value, usage_list_position)
}

impl<K, V> LRUCache<K, V>
where
    K: Eq + Hash + Clone,
    V: Clone,
{
    pub fn new(capacity: usize) -> Self {
        LRUCache {
            capacity,
            map: HashMap::new(),
            usage: LinkedList::new(),
        }
    }

    pub fn get(&mut self, key: &K) -> Option<V> {
        if let Some((val, _)) = self.map.get(key) {
            // Move key to the front (most recently used)
            self.promote_key(key);
            Some(val.clone())
        } else {
            None
        }
    }

    pub fn put(&mut self, key: K, value: V) {
        if self.map.contains_key(&key) {
            // Update value and promote to front
            self.promote_key(&key);
            self.map.insert(key.clone(), (value, 0)); // usage position not used in this impl
        } else {
            if self.map.len() == self.capacity {
                // Evict least recently used key
                if let Some(lru_key) = self.usage.pop_back() {
                    self.map.remove(&lru_key);
                }
            }
            self.usage.push_front(key.clone());
            self.map.insert(key, (value, 0));
        }
    }

    fn promote_key(&mut self, key: &K) {
        // Move key to the front of usage list
        self.usage.retain(|k| k != key);
        self.usage.push_front(key.clone());
    }
}

#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;

    #[test]
    fn test_lru_cache() {
        let mut cache = LRUCache::new(2);
        cache.put(1, 1);
        cache.put(2, 2);
        assert_eq!(cache.get(&1), Some(1)); // cache hit, so order: [1,2]
        cache.put(3, 3); // evicts key 2, order: [3,1]
        assert_eq!(cache.get(&2), None);
        assert_eq!(cache.get(&3), Some(3)); // order now: [3,1]
        cache.put(4, 4); // evicts key 1, order: [4,3]
        assert_eq!(cache.get(&1), None);
        assert_eq!(cache.get(&3), Some(3));
        assert_eq!(cache.get(&4), Some(4));
    }
}

fn main() {
    let mut cache = LRUCache::new(2);
    cache.put("apple", 3);
    cache.put("banana", 5);
    println!("apple: {:?}", cache.get(&"apple")); // Some(3)
    cache.put("pear", 8); // "banana" will be evicted
    println!("banana: {:?}", cache.get(&"banana")); // None
    println!("pear: {:?}", cache.get(&"pear")); // Some(8)
}
```

---

**Features:**
- `put(key, val)`: Insert or update value; evicts least recently used if at capacity.
- `get(key)`: Returns value if exists, and promotes key to most-recently used.
- Generic for any types implementing `Eq`, `Hash`, `Clone`.

**Notes:**
- To run, copy the code into a `main.rs` or paste in [Rust Playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/).
- The usage list tracks the order; `promote_key` moves a key to the front.
- The code is simple and readable; for maximum performance, you can use `std::collections::VecDeque` + HashMap with indices, but this is idiomatic and correct.

