Certainly! Below is a **complete, working Rust implementation** to serialize and deserialize a binary tree. Serialization uses a **preorder traversal** and includes `"null"` or `"#"` for empty nodes, so the tree structure is preserved.

### 1. Define the Tree Structure
```rust
use std::rc::Rc;
use std::cell::RefCell;

#[derive(Debug, PartialEq, Eq)]
pub struct TreeNode {
    pub val: i32,
    pub left: Option<Rc<RefCell<TreeNode>>>,
    pub right: Option<Rc<RefCell<TreeNode>>>,
}

impl TreeNode {
    pub fn new(val: i32) -> Rc<RefCell<TreeNode>> {
        Rc::new(RefCell::new(TreeNode {
            val,
            left: None,
            right: None,
        }))
    }
}
```

### 2. Serialization
We'll use preorder traversal and output a comma-separated string.
```rust
pub fn serialize(root: Option<Rc<RefCell<TreeNode>>>) -> String {
    fn helper(node: Option<Rc<RefCell<TreeNode>>>, out: &mut Vec<String>) {
        if let Some(n) = node {
            let n = n.borrow();
            out.push(n.val.to_string());
            helper(n.left.clone(), out);
            helper(n.right.clone(), out);
        } else {
            out.push("#".to_string());
        }
    }
    let mut vec = Vec::new();
    helper(root, &mut vec);
    vec.join(",")
}
```

### 3. Deserialization
We parse the string and rebuild the tree recursively.
```rust
pub fn deserialize(data: &str) -> Option<Rc<RefCell<TreeNode>>> {
    fn helper<'a, I: Iterator<Item = &'a str>>(iter: &mut I) -> Option<Rc<RefCell<TreeNode>>> {
        if let Some(val) = iter.next() {
            if val == "#" {
                None
            } else {
                let node = TreeNode::new(val.parse().unwrap());
                {
                    let mut n = node.borrow_mut();
                    n.left = helper(iter);
                    n.right = helper(iter);
                }
                Some(node)
            }
        } else {
            None
        }
    }
    let mut iter = data.split(',');
    helper(&mut iter)
}
```

### 4. Example & Test

```rust
fn main() {
    // Construct the tree:
    //      1
    //     / \
    //    2   3
    //       / \
    //      4   5

    let root = TreeNode::new(1);
    root.borrow_mut().left = Some(TreeNode::new(2));
    let right = TreeNode::new(3);
    right.borrow_mut().left = Some(TreeNode::new(4));
    right.borrow_mut().right = Some(TreeNode::new(5));
    root.borrow_mut().right = Some(right);

    let serialized = serialize(Some(root.clone()));
    println!("Serialized: {}", serialized);

    let deserialized = deserialize(&serialized);

    // Just show that serialization -> deserialization gives same tree
    assert_eq!(serialize(deserialized.clone()), serialized);

    println!("Deserialized and verified successfully!");
}
```

