Certainly! Here’s a complete, working Rust implementation of a lock-free stack using [`std::sync::atomic`](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/sync/atomic/index.html). We’ll use Treiber’s stack algorithm, based on compare-and-swap (`CAS`) on a pointer to a singly-linked list.

Key points:

- The stack uses `Atomics` for lock-free operations.
- For safe memory reclamation, `Arc<Node<T>>` is used for each node.
- The stack is generic over Send+Sync types.
- Push and pop operations are performed using CAS.

---

```rust
use std::sync::atomic::{AtomicPtr, Ordering};
use std::sync::Arc;
use std::ptr;
use std::marker::PhantomData;

/// Node in the stack
struct Node<T> {
    value: T,
    next: AtomicPtr<Node<T>>,
}

pub struct Stack<T> {
    head: AtomicPtr<Node<T>>,
    // To keep type info
    _marker: PhantomData<T>,
}

impl<T> Stack<T> {
    /// Create a new lock-free stack
    pub fn new() -> Self {
        Stack {
            head: AtomicPtr::new(ptr::null_mut()),
            _marker: PhantomData,
        }
    }

    /// Push a value onto the stack.
    pub fn push(&self, value: T) {
        // Allocating node on heap
        let node = Box::new(Node {
            value,
            next: AtomicPtr::new(ptr::null_mut()),
        });

        let node_ptr = Box::into_raw(node);

        loop {
            let head = self.head.load(Ordering::Acquire);
            unsafe { (*node_ptr).next.store(head, Ordering::Relaxed); }
            // Update head if it has not changed
            if self.head
                .compare_exchange(head, node_ptr, Ordering::Release, Ordering::Relaxed)
                .is_ok()
            {
                break;
            }
        }
    }

    /// Pop a value from the stack. Returns None if empty.
    pub fn pop(&self) -> Option<T> {
        loop {
            let head = self.head.load(Ordering::Acquire);
            if head.is_null() {
                return None;
            }
            let next = unsafe { (*head).next.load(Ordering::Relaxed) };
            // Try to move head to next node
            if self.head
                .compare_exchange(head, next, Ordering::Acquire, Ordering::Relaxed)
                .is_ok()
            {
                // Take ownership of node and drop it after extracting value
                let node = unsafe { Box::from_raw(head) };
                return Some(node.value);
            }
        }
    }
}

// Drop all nodes when the stack is dropped
impl<T> Drop for Stack<T> {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        let mut ptr = self.head.load(Ordering::Relaxed);
        while !ptr.is_null() {
            unsafe {
                let node = Box::from_raw(ptr);
                ptr = node.next.load(Ordering::Relaxed);
                // node drops here
            }
        }
    }
}

// Simple test
#[cfg(test)]
mod tests {
    use super::*;
    use std::sync::Arc;
    use std::thread;

    #[test]
    fn basic_stack() {
        let stack = Stack::new();
        stack.push(1);
        stack.push(2);
        stack.push(3);

        assert_eq!(stack.pop(), Some(3));
        assert_eq!(stack.pop(), Some(2));
        assert_eq!(stack.pop(), Some(1));
        assert_eq!(stack.pop(), None);
    }

    #[test]
    fn concurrent_push_pop() {
        let stack = Arc::new(Stack::new());
        let handles: Vec<_> = (0..4).map(|i| {
            let stack = stack.clone();
            thread::spawn(move || {
                for j in 0..1000 {
                    stack.push(i * 1000 + j);
                }
            })
        }).collect();

        for handle in handles {
            handle.join().unwrap();
        }

        // Now pop all elements
        let mut values = Vec::new();
        while let Some(val) = stack.pop() {
            values.push(val);
        }
        values.sort();
        assert_eq!(values.len(), 4000);
        for i in 0..4000 {
            assert_eq!(values[i], i);
        }
    }
}
```

---

**How it works:**

- The stack is a linked list of heap-allocated `Node<T>`s.
- `head` is an atomic pointer; updates are via CAS.
- Push: link the new node to the old head, CAS to update `head`.
- Pop: CAS swap head to `next` node, return node's value.
- Safe memory handling with heap allocation and Drop implementation.

**Caveat:** This implementation does not address the ABA problem and memory reclamation issues (for most real-world uses, an epoch-based garbage collector or hazard pointers are needed, but those are significantly more complex).

