Here is a complete, **working Rust implementation** for the N-Queens problem. This implementation finds all distinct solutions for placing N queens on an NxN chessboard so that no two queens threaten each other. Each solution is represented as a vector containing the column position of the queen in each row.

```rust
fn solve_n_queens(n: usize) -> Vec<Vec<String>> {
    let mut solutions = Vec::new();
    let mut board = vec![vec!['.'; n]; n];
    backtrack(0, n, &mut board, &mut solutions);
    solutions
}

fn backtrack(row: usize, n: usize, board: &mut Vec<Vec<char>>, solutions: &mut Vec<Vec<String>>) {
    if row == n {
        let solution = board.iter()
            .map(|r| r.iter().collect())
            .collect();
        solutions.push(solution);
        return;
    }
    for col in 0..n {
        if is_safe(board, row, col, n) {
            board[row][col] = 'Q';
            backtrack(row + 1, n, board, solutions);
            board[row][col] = '.';
        }
    }
}

fn is_safe(board: &Vec<Vec<char>>, row: usize, col: usize, n: usize) -> bool {
    // Check column
    for i in 0..row {
        if board[i][col] == 'Q' {
            return false;
        }
    }
    // Check diagonal \
    let mut i = row as isize - 1;
    let mut j = col as isize - 1;
    while i >= 0 && j >= 0 {
        if board[i as usize][j as usize] == 'Q' {
            return false;
        }
        i -= 1;
        j -= 1;
    }
    // Check diagonal /
    let mut i = row as isize - 1;
    let mut j = col as isize + 1;
    while i >= 0 && j < n as isize {
        if board[i as usize][j as usize] == 'Q' {
            return false;
        }
        i -= 1;
        j += 1;
    }
    true
}

// Print solutions in a readable format
fn print_solutions(solutions: &[Vec<String>]) {
    for (idx, solution) in solutions.iter().enumerate() {
        println!("Solution {}:", idx + 1);
        for row in solution {
            println!("{}", row);
        }
        println!();
    }
}

fn main() {
    let n = 8;
    let solutions = solve_n_queens(n);
    println!("Number of solutions for {}-Queens: {}\n", n, solutions.len());
    print_solutions(&solutions);
}
```

### Features:
- **Backtracking algorithm** for exploring placements.
- **Safety checks** for columns and diagonals.
- **Returns all distinct solutions** as board layouts.
- **Readable printing** of board representations.

